  RELEVANCE: This foundational paper empirically validates key predictions of extended mind theory regarding memory transformation through tool use. The "Google effect" shows how ubiquitous internet access can restructure cognitive practices from internal storage to external access, paralleling how Otto's notebook functioned in Clark and Chalmers' original extended mind example. The research raises questions about whether this cognitive restructuring constitutes genuine cognitive extension or problematic dependence.

  POSITION: Empirical demonstration of internet-mediated memory transformation, supporting transactive memory accounts of digital cognitive extension.
  },
  keywords = {Google-effect, transactive-memory, internet, High},
  abstract = {Owing to Internet search, we are more likely to encode “where” aspects of memory rather than “what.”},
